{{Infobox book | name = Far-Fetched Facts. A Parable of Development Aid | image = Cover of Far-Fetched Facts.jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Hardcover edition | author = [[Richard Rottenburg]] | title_orig = Weit hergeholte Fakten | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = German | series = | subject = | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = [[MIT Press]] | pub_date = 2009 | media_type = Print | pages = 280 | isbn = 978-0262182645 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} {{economic anthropology}}
'''''Far-fetched facts''''' is a book by German [[anthropologist]] [[Richard Rottenburg]] published in German as ''Weit hergeholte Fakten'' in 2002; the English translation was released in 2009. The book is an [[ethnography|ethnography-based]], though fictionalized, [[polyphonic]] account of a waterworks improvement project in Tanzania (called Ruritania in the books fictionalization). The book follows the different stages of the development project by looking closely at the interactions between a Northern development bank, experts of an international consulting firm and African project managers. It focuses thereby on technologies of inscription that enable the reconnaissance and [[operationalization]] of improvement measures to be taken, but also guide the overall interaction between the different stakeholders of the project. Showing these representational and managerial practices the book lays bare the necessary day-to-day production of objectivity and legitimacy in development projects, but also the intricacies and inconsistencies of daily translation processes, that often lead to the rather disappointing results of such development enterprises. Inspired by [[Organizational studies|organizational]] and [[science and technology studies]] “Far-fetched facts” provides an anthropological critique of the aid industry in Africa distinct from [[Postdevelopment theory|postdevelopment critique]].
==Reviews== *[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.1086/657229?uid=3737864&uid=2&uid=4&sid=21101752775583 Breyman, Steve 2010. Review of Far-Fetched Facts. In: The History of Science Society, vol. 101, no. 3, pp. 682-683] Retrieved March 13, 2013. *[http://www.uni-bonn.de/~hevers/papers/Evers2004-Rottenburg.pdf Evers, Hans-Dieter 2004. Buchbesprechung. Weither geholte Fakten. Eine Parabel der Entwicklungshilfe. In: Zeitschrift für Ethnologie 129, p 167-168] Retrieved March 13, 2013. *[http://www.faz.net/aktuell/feuilleton/buecher/rezension-sachbuch-es-muss-umgekrempelt-sein-11323422.html Rosenfelder, Andreas. Es muß umgekrempelt sein. In FAZ December 3, 2002] Retrieved February 6, 2013.
